    "philosophy": "Josko Gravner is the godfather of modern orange wine. After a transformative trip to Georgia in 2000, he abandoned stainless steel and barriques for buried Georgian qvevri (clay amphorae). All wines undergo extended skin maceration — whites ferment on skins for 5-7 months in qvevri, followed by years of aging in large Slavonian oak. No temperature control, no selected yeasts, no sulfites added during fermentation, no fining, no filtration. Biodynamic farming since 2012. The estate sits in Oslavia, a hillside hamlet on the Slovenian border known for its ponca soils (layered flysch of compressed marl and sandstone). Gravner's radical return to ancient methods in the early 2000s helped launch the global orange wine movement.",
