      "historical_note": "Josko Gravner was initially a modernist — among the first in Friuli to use barriques and temperature-controlled fermentation in the 1980s. After a devastating 1997 hailstorm destroyed 80% of the harvest, he began questioning modern winemaking. A 2000 trip to Georgia, where he discovered 8,000-year-old qvevri traditions, changed everything. He abandoned all modern technology, buried Georgian clay vessels in his cellar, and returned to pre-industrial winemaking. The wine world initially dismissed him; now he is recognized as a visionary.",
      "key_dates": {
        "1973": "Josko takes over from father, begins modernizing",
        "1987": "First barrique-aged wines, critical acclaim",
        "1997": "Devastating hailstorm — catalyst for philosophical shift",
        "2000": "First trip to Georgia, discovers qvevri",
        "2001": "First vintage fermented in qvevri (Ribolla)",
        "2007": "Abandons DOC Collio designation, declassifies to IGT Venezia Giulia",
        "2012": "Begins biodynamic practices",
        "2018": "Mateja Gravner joins full-time"
      }
    }
  },
  "_notes": {
    "scope": "Complete current Gravner portfolio — 4 wines. Gravner's production is tiny (~35,000 bottles/year total) and releases are very delayed (5-7 years after vintage). Only scores from major publications are included — many vintages have few or no published scores because Gravner rarely submits to critics. Older pre-qvevri vintages are excluded as they represent a fundamentally different winemaking approach.",
    "appellations": "Gravner voluntarily left the DOC Collio system in 2007, finding it too restrictive for his methods. All wines since 2007 are labeled IGT Venezia Giulia. Pre-2007 wines were DOC Collio or DOC Friuli Isonzo.",
    "orange_wine_note": "Gravner's Ribolla and Breg are orange wines — white grapes with extended skin maceration (5-7 months on skins). The 'orange' color value in this file is intentional and tests the CHECK constraint. These are not white wines — the extended skin contact gives them deep amber/orange color, tannic structure, and oxidative complexity.",
    "score_sourcing": "Scores from Wine Advocate (Monica Larner for Italy), Vinous (Antonio Galloni), James Suckling. Gravner wines are notoriously hard to score — critics often struggle with the style. Many vintages go unreviewed."
